<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0321</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ME Association - Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Re Draft Deregulation Bill – Clause 35</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Thank you for asking me to comment on the proposal  that is contained in clause 35 of the Draft Deregulation Bill.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clause 35 relates specifically to the Government's intention </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to remove the duty on the Senior President of Tribunals to report on the standards of decision making by the DWP following the abolition of the Administrative Justice and Tribunals Council and the merger of the Tribunals Service with HM Courts Service.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In practical terms, I understand this will mean that the Senior President of the Tribunals </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will no longer have to prepare an annual report on the performance of DWP decision making as introduced under section 15A of the Social Security Act. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Consequently, there will be limited transparency about the assessment of decision making in relation to key benefits such as the Employment and Support Allowance (ESA). This is a vital issue for people with a range of fluctuating medical conditions, as well as those with mental health conditions. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I am an honorary medical adviser to The ME Association but am also commenting in my capacity as a member of the Forward ME Group (a group of charities concerned with ME/CFS which is chaired by the Countess of Mar) and a member of the Fluctuating Conditions Group (FCG).  The FCG is a group of representatives from medical charities for people with fluctuating medical conditions.  The group has produced recommendations for changes to the Work Capability Assessment (WCA). Our recommendations, along with those from a mental health group,  are now being compared to the current WCA by the DWP in an evidence based review.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I am very concerned by and completely opposed to this proposal.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The reasons for doing so are set out below and I have included important supporting evidence from the three annual independent reviews of the WCA that have been carried out by Professor Malcolm Harrington. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Information relating to the DWP decision making and appeal procedures that is contained in these reviews should certainly be brought to the attention of the committee.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Background</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Individuals applying for Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) have a right of appeal against decisions taken on behalf of the Secretary of State. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This means that they are entitled to have the decision examined by a body that is independent of the Department and its decision-making structures. These appeals are carried out by the First-tier Tribunal of the Social Entitlement Chamber and administered by the Tribunals Service, an executive body of the Ministry of Justice. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, it is widely accepted by all concerned – claimants, patient support charities, the DWP, the Tribunal Service – that far too many people are taking their case to appeal.  The very high rate of success at appeal – somewhere around 40% of cases being heard – clearly indicates that there are major problems with the ESA decision making process.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The failure to get so many decisions right first time, at the level of the DWP Decision Maker, has led to increased pressure on the First-tier and Tribunals Service. In practical terms this means that large amounts of professional time and public money are being wasted on reversing decisions that were not properly considered in the first place.  It also places a considerable amount of stress on many genuine claimants – which may then result in a significant deterioration in their health.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The majority of DWP decisions that are overturned are because the Tribunal was able to obtain additional information that was not available to the DWP Decision Maker, through oral evidence elicited by the Tribunal, or through additional medical evidence brought along to the appeal.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The following comments from Dr Jane Rayner, Chief Medical Member of the Social Security Appeals Tribunal Service, are extremely relevant here and are recorded in the Minutes of the Forward ME Group meeting held on 26 January 2011:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 15pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Dr Rayner said that she had met Professor Malcolm Harrington and she had told him that sometimes, when she read a report, she had an image of an individual in her mind but when they appeared before her the person bore no resemblance to the person portrayed in the report and that it was as if the report had been written by somebody completely different. She had also encountered cases where examining doctors had insisted that the claimant sign their medical report without having been allowed to see it.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 15pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">After being told that most people with chronic conditions want to concentrate on the things they are able to do and found it very hard to describe what they could not do, some of which they found embarrassing to describe, Dr Rayner said that people must leave the tribunals procedure with their dignity intact. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 15pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">They were exercising their right to an appeal and the tribunals system should act as a safety net for those who have been incorrectly assessed.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Dr Rayner was asked whether the system was coping with its current workload, and whether it would cope in the future as claimants were migrated from incapacity benefit to employment and support allowance (ESA). Dr </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Rayner replied they were not currently coping which was why they have just appointed 200 new doctors. Their workload had increased. They used to work at 250,000 appeals a year. That had now risen to 500,000 appeals a year following the introduction of ESA.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Minutes of Forward ME Group for 26/01/2011:</span><a href="http://www.forward-me.org.uk/26th%20january%202011.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.forward-me.org.uk/26th%20january%202011.htm</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The background information I have summarized so far partly explains why the DWP set up a series of independent annual reviews of the WCA – the first three being carried out by Professor Malcolm Harrington; the final two being carried out by Dr Paul Litchfield. Part of this process also involved two groups covering fluctuating medical conditions and mental health conditions being set up to produce recommendations as to how the WCA could be made more fair and effective – action which has now resulted in the Evidence Based Review that I have already referred to..</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To fully understand the complex background to these concerns about the entire decision making process the committee needs to consult the relevant chapters, along with the conclusions and recommendations relating to decision-making and appeals procedures, in the three annual reviews that have so far been prepared by Professor Harrington.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The most relevant sections are listed below:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2010 Review:  </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/work-capability-assessment-independent-review-year-1"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/work-capability-assessment-independent-review-year-1</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Chapter 7: Appeals</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Annex A: Recommendations 15 – 17 on Appeal Procedures</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2011 Review: </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/work-capability-assessment-independent-review-year-2"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/work-capability-assessment-independent-review-year-2</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Chapter 6: Training – Appeals Judges and Medical Members, paras 16 - 22</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2012 Review: </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/work-capability-assessment-independent-review-year-3"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/work-capability-assessment-independent-review-year-3</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Chapter 2: Implementation of the year one and year two recommendations – The decision making process, paras 60 – 70 and The Appeals process, paras 71 – 76.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Despite three reviews and a large number of recommendations for change there is still a great deal of work to be done in relation to improving the whole decision-making process and reducing the workload on the Tribunals. This involves both Decision Makers and the Tribunal Service – something that is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">made clear in the section covering ‘The appeals process’ in Professor Harrington’s 2012 review:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The appeals process</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">71.The appeals process remains an area of considerable concern for the Review. The First-tier Tribunal President opines that this is outside the remit of the Review. The Review disagrees. Appeals are a fundamental part of the overall WCA process.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">72.The Review believes that two aspects need to be addressed with some urgency. Firstly, it is imperative that we get to the stage where Tribunal members are making their decisions based on the same evidence as the Decision Maker.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">73.Secondly, the Decision Maker Reasoning comes into play. The Review wrote to the Minister for Employment about this in May 2012 (Annex 2) indicating that not only should the Decision Maker Reasoning become the backbone of DWP’s case, but that if that detailed explanation is to be overturned by the Tribunal then they in turn must provide detailed justification for their decision. This would make the whole process more transparent and more accountable.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">74.To date, the only feedback secured from First-tier Tribunals (across all health and benefits appeals) has been, at long last, Judges indicating which one reason from a drop-down menu of one-liners is the basis for the Tribunal overturning the decision.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">75.This rudimentary form of feedback has taken much time and effort to achieve and it followed a recommendation to Ministers in February 2012 (Annex 2).The list of reasons available to Judges are:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">v</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">v</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-